The problem is in this calculation:

```javascript
array[i].map(x =&gt; Math.pow(x, array[i].indexOf(x) + 1))
```

When you get to the number `1676`, it has repeating digit `6`, so `indexOf(6)` will return the first index twice, thus you get

[1&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;, 6&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;, 7&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;, 6&lt;sup&gt;**2**&lt;/sup&gt;]

instead of

[1&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;, 6&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;, 7&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;, 6&lt;sup&gt;**4**&lt;/sup&gt;]

A similar problem happens with **2**4**2**7.

You can simply use the second argument to the [`Array#map`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map) callback to get the current index:

```javascript
array[i].map((x, index) =&gt; Math.pow(x, index + 1))
```





